<li><div class="entry" id="ljcmt661165"><div class="entryheader">
<h3 class="entrysubject"></h3><div class="entryposter"><span class='ljuser with-alias-value ljuser-name_wotw' lj:user='wotw' style='white-space: nowrap;'><a href='http://wotw.livejournal.com/profile'><img src='http://l-stat.livejournal.com/img/userinfo.gif' alt='[info]' width='17' height='17' style='vertical-align: bottom; border: 0; padding-right: 1px;' /></a><a href='http://wotw.livejournal.com/'><b>wotw</b></a></span></div><div class="entrytimestamp"><span class="entrytimestampdate"><span title="44 minutes after journal entry">9/1/06 05:28 pm (UTC)</span></span></div><div class="entrylinkbarpre">              </div>
<div class="entryuserpic"><img src="http://l-userpic.livejournal.com/62888836/447044" title="" alt=""height="100" width="95"  /></div></div>

<div class="entrycontent">As one who frequently asks "Well, why don't they all just $action?",<br />let me point out that this is never (in my case) and rarely (in most<br />other people's cases, at least in my experience) intended as a <br />solution to the problem; instead, it's intended as a first step toward<br />a better understanding of why the simple solutions don't work, which is<br />likely to be useful knowledge in the construction of a better solution.<br /><br />And now you know why I get all bent when some idiot refuses to tackle<br />some complex social issue by ignoring questions of the form "Well,<br />why don't they all just $action?".</div>

